            <biogHist>
                <p>Archibald MacDonald was the son of Donald, ferryman, and Catherine MacDonald née
                    Stewart. By 1851, with his age given as 21, Archibald is described as a
                    shoemaker in Newton, Trumisgarry with his brother Alan (18) as a tailor. At the
                    time of the 1861 census he is listed together with his older sister Mary in
                    Newton. In 1867 he married Margaret Macaulay and by the time of the 1881 census
                    they appear to have had three children: Catherine (12), Donald (9) and Angus
                    (6). By 1891 he is widowed and living with his unmarried daughter Catherine, at
                    that time working as a shoemaker and also as Postmaster; Catherine is described
                    as Post Office Assistant. Ten years later, they have been joined by Archibald
                    MacDonald's two unmarried sons, with Donald described as a carpenter and Angus
                    as a postman.</p>
                <p>Archibald MacDonald died of influenza in Newtonferry, North Uist and his
                    neighbour witnessed the certificate. </p>
                <p>In 1873 Carmichael visited Archibald MacDonald on North Uist and collected a song
                    from him entitled 'Duan Callaig' [The Song of Hogmanay]. </p>
